@startuml upgrade-lifecycle
' Authoritative state diagram for doc/upgrade-timeline.md § Upgrade-row lifecycle.
' States are the public.upgrade.state enum (upgrade_state); the timestamp
' invariants per state are enforced by chk_upgrade_state_attributes — see
' doc/db/table/public_upgrade.md.
' Names: doc/upgrade-vocabulary.md. Decision logic: doc/upgrade-recovery-model.md.
skinparam backgroundColor #FEFEFE
skinparam state {
    BorderColor #1565C0
    BackgroundColor #E3F2FD
    ArrowColor #1565C0
    FontColor #102027
}

title public.upgrade row lifecycle — discovery, execution, and recovery decision tree

legend top
The only way to know these paths actually work is to RUN them — the problem is too hard
to reason out. commit -> push -> CI builds the per-commit image -> run on a real VM ->
observe -> iterate. This diagram is the map (each case + its TEST coverage); the run is
the territory. See doc/install-upgrade-testing.md.
endlegend

[*] --> available : service poll discovers a release

available --> scheduled : operator/CI schedules\n(scheduled_at set)
available --> skipped : operator skips
available --> superseded : newer release discovered

scheduled --> in_progress : service claims\n(started_at set)
scheduled --> superseded : newer release supersedes

in_progress --> completed : all steps OK\n(completed_at set, error NULL)

' [HUMAN: unknown] — unrecognised phase or unrecognised error: stays in_progress, loud
in_progress --> in_progress : [HUMAN: **unknown**]\nunrecognised phase or unrecognised error —\nstays in_progress + loud, waiting for a person\n(systemd-StartLimit backstop surfaces it)

' [PARKED — STATBUS-046] — already-at-new forward exhausted the crash-resume death
' budget (3 process deaths) OR hit same-step-twice (deterministic hang) OR a B/C failure fired:
' stays in_progress (forward-only preserved; rollback stays reachable ONLY via a
' cannot-reach-new verdict, NEVER via exhaustion). The row gains
' recovery_parked_at + recovery_parked_reason; the service SKIPS resume
' (alive-idle, no crash loop) and the degraded siren fires ONCE. This is what
' replaces rune's loop-forever (10,229 restarts).
in_progress --> in_progress : [PARKED — **STATBUS-046**]\nalready-at-new forward: budget (3 process deaths) exhausted, same-step-twice,\nor a B/C failure — PARK (recovery_parked_at + reason).\nService skips resume (alive-idle), siren once.\nUn-park ONLY via a deliberate operator trigger (re-schedule / ./sb install)

' cannot-reach-new → roll back (also: intermittent exhausted backoff-retry, or persistent error)
in_progress --> rolled_back : **cannot-reach-new** (observed-state) → roll back\nOR intermittent error exhausted **backoff-retry** → roll back\nOR persistent error (zero retries) → roll back\n(rolled_back_at + error)

' [HUMAN: restore-broke] — rollback chosen but restore itself failed
in_progress --> failed : [HUMAN: **restore-broke**]\nrollback chosen; restore itself failed\n(rsync/disk; never substitute another backup)\n(error, no rolled_back_at)

note right of in_progress
  Full recovery decision — doc/upgrade-recovery-model.md §1–§4:

  **§1  Read the upgrade-in-progress marker**
  no marker          → normal start [auto]
  corrupt/unreadable → discard-and-log → normal start [auto]
  install-holder     → clear, no DB work [auto]
  unrecognized phase → [HUMAN: unknown] (self-loop above)
  recognized phase   → §2

  **§2  Decide direction (observed-state)**
  old-sb-upgrading (before booting the new binary) → roll back trivially (nothing changed) [auto]
  new-sb-swapped, already-at-new        → continue-upgrade / complete-upgrade → completed [auto]
  new-sb-upgrading, cannot-reach-new    → roll back → rolled_back [auto]
  new-sb-upgrading, can't-read-position → §3 (intermittent error)

  **§3  Error classifier (no-spin rule)**
  intermittent (db-unreachable / commit-not-fetched)
    → backoff-retry (in-process + heartbeating)
    resolves → continue → completed
    exhausts → no longer transient → roll back → rolled_back
  persistent (same error every time)
    → roll back, zero retries → rolled_back
  unknown (unrecognised)
    → [HUMAN: unknown] self-loop; stays in_progress + loud

  **§4  Terminals**
  completed          — forward succeeded [auto]
  rolled_back        — rollback succeeded; healthy on old version [auto]
  failed             — [HUMAN: restore-broke] restore itself broke
  (in_progress loop) — [HUMAN: unknown] waits for a person

  **§5  Park (STATBUS-046 — already-at-new forward, can't roll back)**
  Forward, after booting the new binary, keeps failing already-at-new
  (integrators may have written past the maintenance-off point → rollback
  forbidden). The bound is a crash-resume DEATH BUDGET (3 process deaths;
  recovery_attempts counted at attempt START so a death self-counts, deaths =
  attempts-1), plus same-step-twice → deterministic-hang park, plus B/C
  failures → park on first. On terminal:
    already-at-new        → PARK  (recovery_parked_at + reason; stays in_progress)
    data-safe/cannot-reach-new → roll back (039 direction; 110 makes it byte-safe)
  A parked row is SKIPPED by every automatic resume (alive-idle, siren once).

  **§6  STATBUS-145 — the delta leaves the boot window; park shrinks**
  boot-migrate now catches the schema up ONLY to the daemon floor; the upgrade
  DELTA runs once at the applyPostSwap migrate step. So on a resume the delta is
  PENDING → observed state reads cannot-reach-new (Behind) → the disposition is
  ROLLBACK, not park, for EVERY pre-delta step failure (config, pull, db-up,
  reconnect, AND deterministic B/C — §3/§5 park-on-first now applies only
  at-target). PARK shrinks to exactly two cases: (a) repeated process deaths at
  pre-delta steps (RecoveryBudgetGuard, canRollBack=false), and (b) a POST-delta
  at-target failure (the health-check window). Upgrades are effectively ATOMIC:
  apply the delta once, restore on any interruption.
  UN-PARK = the two deliberate operator triggers only (re-schedule / ./sb
  install) — each buys exactly ONE fresh attempt with a reset budget.
end note

rolled_back --> dismissed : operator acknowledges
failed --> dismissed : operator acknowledges

completed --> [*]
skipped --> [*]
superseded --> [*]
dismissed --> [*]

note bottom
  chk_upgrade_state_attributes enforces the timestamp columns per state
  (e.g. completed ⇒ completed_at NOT NULL, error NULL; rolled_back ⇒
  rolled_back_at + error NOT NULL; failed ⇒ error NOT NULL, no rolled_back_at).
  rolled_back = [auto] snapshot restored, healthy at the old version.
  failed = [HUMAN: restore-broke] rollback's restore itself broke — box cannot reach runnable state.
  (in_progress loop) = [HUMAN: unknown] unrecognised phase or error — waits for a person.
  Decision logic: doc/upgrade-recovery-model.md · Names: doc/upgrade-vocabulary.md
end note

@enduml
